Multijet events produced in hard QCD processes may be selected, even though there is no primary lepton from a weak-boson decay. This may happen if a jet is misidentified as an isolated lepton, leading to a so-called fake lepton, or if the event has a non-prompt lepton from a hadron decay which appears to be isolated. The misidentification of jets as leptons is difficult to model in the detector simulation, which is why two specific requirements are included in the event selection to reduce the multijet background without significantly reducing the signal efficiency. The first such requirement uses the transverse mass of the lepton–ETmiss\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
