				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_{\text {T}}^{\text {miss}}$$\end{document}. There are two jets in the events considered and exactly one of the jets is required to be b-tagged. The pseudo top quark is then formed by adding the four-momenta of the W boson and the b-tagged jet.

A neural network (NN) [72] is employed to separate signal from background events, by combining several kinematic variables into an optimised NN discriminant (ONN\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$O_{\text {NN}}$$\end{document}). The reconstruction of top-quark-related kinematic variables, the ranking of input variables according to their discriminating power, and the training process of the NN follow closely the procedures used in previous ATLAS publications about t-channel single top-quark production [9, 10].

